card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. haynaldianum (Purple Wings x Ron)
card.name: Paphiopedilum haynaldianum

card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. rothschildianum x sib ('Giant Wings' GM/WOC x '2nd Dimension')
We all know about Giant Wings - from one of the best Japanese breeding. 2nd Dimension first bloomed with four gigantic flowers with almost 7cm dorsal and 30cm ns. We look for color, size and form!
card.name: Paphiopedilum rothschidianum

card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. rothschildianum x sib ('Giant Wings' GM/WOC x 'X-Hot' SSM/JOGA)
Sibling cross of two of the best Japanese breeding! Giant Wings awarded for his dark color at the WOC while X-Hot is GM quality and is very dark color. This is our best sibling cross of Japanese Strain!
card.name: Paphiopedilum rothschildianum

card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. supardii x sib ('Dragon Dance' x 'Golden Boy')
Both parents are from second germination line breeding of this species. Both parents have five flowers.
card.name: Paphiopedilum supardii

card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. stonei x sib ('New Dimension' x 'The Best')
New Dimension is one of the best from our PAS0030. The Best is originated from late Ray Rands collection and it is the best stonei he had. Now we crossed New Dimension back to one of it's parent.
card.name: Paphiopedilum stonei

card.desc:
From Orchid Inn.   	
Paph. Hsinying Luke 'Omaha' AM/AOS x adductum var. anitum 'Ace' AM/AOS
anitum has been proved to be a great parent and specially with Brachy. Omaha is very round and large. First few bloomed have burgundy color flowers with dark chocolate stripes.
card.name: Paphiopedilum (Hsyinying Luke x adductum var. anitum)
Paphiopedilum (Hsyinying Luke x adductum var. anitum)

cards.desc: http://www.twyst.org/atlos
cards.name: Draft booklet format can be found at http://www.twyst.org/atlos

cards.desc: A small growing species from Madagascar that is found at a variety of elevations and is warm to cool growing.   Flowers are produced primarily from spring into autumn.
cards.name: Angraecum didieri (3" basket blooming size)

cards.desc: A very dwarf species from northern Madagascar.  This small plant is already producing several offsets.   The 2" flowers are long lasting and have a slender nectar spur much longer than the flower.   Late winter to early spring blooming.
cards.name: Angraecum equitans (2" basket in pot blooming size)

cards.desc: http://www.orchidspecies.com/angdendrobiopsis.htm
cards.name: Angraecum dendrobiopsis (seedling)

cards.desc: donated by ABG
cards.name: Aeranthes arachnites (two seedlings)

cards.desc: An interesting species from the foothills of the Himalayas that produces dense clusters of many tiny yellow flowers with dense purple spotting and an interesting, but not unpleasant scent.   Donated by Veronique Perrot.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum careyanum - blooming size

cards.desc: There are already 11 AOS awards for this showy, is somewhat smelly, cross by Bill Thomas, including an FCC of 94 points.    Flowers average around 3 inches in width and 4 inches in height.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum More Than Aghast ('Foxy' x 'Big Ben') - 1 "large" seedling size from flask by Bill Thoms

cards.desc: A miniature species with brightly colored flower clusters from the mountains of  China, Laos, Taiwan and Vietnam.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum tingabarinum

cards.desc: A sister of the famous Bulb. Elizabeth Ann 'Buckleberry' FCC/AOS, with somewhat smaller and paler flowers, but can become a substantial specimen.   The specimen photo is a plant grown by Marble Branch Farms that recieved a 95 point CCE on Hallowwen Day in 2009 with 558 flowers. This plant donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum Elizabeth Ann 'Jean' HCC/AOS

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum sp. (bare root cutting)

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum corolliferum (bare root cutting)

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum masdevalliaceum (bare root cutting)

cards.desc: A good sized (but not yet fully grown) plant with leaves up to 22 inches long.  One of those bulbophyllums that looks so neat you can almost tolerate the smell.  A picture of the actual plant is attached.  The flower picture is an example of the species.  Donated by Roy Harrow, previously grown by Richard Hallberg.
cards.name: Bulbophyllum phalaenopsis

cards.desc:
From orchidspecies.com "Found in Sri Lanka, India, Nepal, Bhutan, Sikkim, Guangdong, Guangxi, Hong Kong, Hunan, southeastern Tibet and southern Yunan provinces of China, Hong Kong, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak Borneo, Java, Sumatra, Sulawesi and the Ryukyus Islands in temperate forests at elevations of 400 to 1500 meters as a small sized, hot to cool growing terrestrial orchid with small, narrowly conical pseudobulbs and several, plicate, broadly elliptic, acute, narrowing below into the petiolate or sessile base leaves that blooms in the late summmer and early fall on an erect, 5 to 6" [12.5 to 15 cm] long, successively several to many [10 to 15] flowered inflorescence."
A very unusual and uncommon species!
cards.name: Calanthe masuca (syn. Cal. kintaroi) 'La Rocaille' x self (3.5" pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: New hybrid for compact spaces - can sit in water when actively growing, but should rest after blooming
cards.name: Gastrophaius Micro Burst 'George's Gold' 4" pot near blooming size

cards.desc: One of the more colorful clones of Gps. Micro Burst (Gastrorchis pulchra x Phaius tankervilleae) that is quick growing and easy to flower.   Terrestrial plant loving filtered light, richer potting mix and moist conditions.   Can be grown with a saucer under the plant to hold excess water.
cards.name: Gastrophaius Micro Burst 'Wild Thing' (4" pot young plant)

cards.desc: An awarded form of Gps. Dan Rosenberg (Gastrorchis tubrculosa x Phaius tankervilleae) that is quick growing and easy to flower.   Terrestrial plant loving filtered light, richer potting mix and moist conditions.   Can be grown with a saucer under the plant to hold excess water.
cards.name: Gastrophaius Dan Rosenberg 'Tropical Ice' HCC/AOS - 4" pot young plant

cards.desc: A division from the owner of the awarded plant, Marilyn LeDoux.   Award description reads:  "Eighteen flat flowers and seven buds on two inflorescences; flowers bright rose-pink, striped darker pink; lip darker pink centrally, white throat; substance average; texture matte."    Winter, spring flowering.
cards.name: Calanthe Rose Georgene 'Electric Pink' HCC/AOS 4" pot division of awarded plant

cards.desc: A newly registered hybrid from this year that produces dense cascading clusters of very fragrant green and white flowers with a fringed lip.   Blooms in late fall into winter and is deciduous.
cards.name: Clowesetum Rebecca Express 'M' (Clowesia Rebecca Northen x Catasetum expansum) 3.5" pot in spike

cards.desc: I managed to secure a few more plants of this mericlone last year.   This one has been grown up for an additional year to be a fully mature blooming size plant capable of producing several spikes this winter.  Wonderfully fragrant.   Definitely the last chance to get this one.
cards.name: Clowesia Rebecca Northen 'Mikabi' (3.5" pot mature blooming size)

cards.desc: A descendant of the famous Rlc. Oconee with large, fragrant, salmon red flowers that could occur almost any season but favoring fall and winter.
cards.name: Rlc. Ahchung Ruby 'Siam' 5" pot near blooming size

cards.desc: This is a descendant of both Rlc. Fortune and Rlc. Toshie Aoki.   The photo is of a sister plant from the same cross, flowers will be similar, large and fragrant and most likely to come in fall to winter.
cards.name: Rlc. Nakornchairsri Delight 'No 3' (5" pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: A famous descendant of Cattleya S. J. Bracey and Cattleya Nigritian, expect fragrant, large,  rich red-purple flowers with a darker lip and yellow throat in fall to spring.
cards.name: Rlc. Tainan City 'General' 5.5" pot blooming size

cards.desc: Another recent introduction with famous parents such as C. Bow Bells and Rlc. Desse.   Fragrant, full flowers on a compact plant generally in fall to winter.   FLowers may have a faint lavender edge to the lip.
cards.name: Rlc. Siam White 'The Best' 5" pot blooming size

cards.desc: Created by the lovely and unique Marilyn LeDoux of Windy Hill Gardens in Labadia, MO, who is a legendary orchid grower with an eye for the unusual and a good sense of humor!  The growth and flowering habits favor the Epicat. parent, but with lots of purple suffusion and more compact size in the plant, and more intense colors in the flower.   Truly something special that you will not be able to find for sale as the entire cross has now sold out.   Purchased as a small seedling in a 2" pot and now close to flowering size.
cards.name: Epicatcyclia Bloody Nose (Epicattleya Ren Marqus x Encyclia phoenicea) 3.5" pot near flowering size

cards.desc: A recent remake of a cross first down in 1908 that produces very compact plants with large, fragrant, colorful flowers.   Photo is from a batch I raised up to bloom in 2004.   The general shape is usually the same, but the color and pattern will vary.  An outstanding and unusual plant to own!
cards.name: Brassocattleya Hippodamia (B. nodosa x C. aclandiae) 3.5" net pot vigorous seedling

cards.desc: A nice compact hybrid between a spotted, fragrant Cattleya and Brassavola nodosa.   Photo shows the potential outcome, though as seedlings, this plant will have its own unique look.  Should flower when young and then improve with age.
cards.name: Brassocattleya Spotted Clown (C. Lulu x B. nodosa) 3.5" pot vigorous seedling

cards.desc: This is a remake of a very successful cross originally registered in 1997.   The photo shows a fairly typical outcome, though the color pattern varies from one to the next.   Easy to grow and bloom.
cards.name: Rhyncobrassoleya Copper Queen (Bc. Richard Mueller x Rlc. Toshie Aoki) 3.5" net pot seedling

cards.desc: This entry is for anyone who has only gotten into orchids in recent years and missed out on owning this breakthrough hybrid from 1965 between Guarianthe aurantiaca and Cattleya guttata.    Very showy and fragrant, long lasting clusters of waxy flowers that start blooming young but improve with age.   Photo shows the original awarded 'Kodama' form that was self pollinated to produce this seedling.   So important of a cross was this, that almost 900 registered hybrids now descend from it!
cards.name: Cattlianthe Chocolate Drop ('Kodama' AM/AOS x self) 3.5" net pot seedling

cards.desc: A long awaited new batch that takes Cty. El Hatillo back to E. tampensis for wonderful wiry, sometimes branched spikes of 2" pale green flowers with a bright purple lip.   Summer flowering - likes a basket or mount when mature.  This plant is a year further along than the plants offered last year and is likely to bloom in 2020.   Second photo shows the results of a mature plant.
cards.name: Catyclia Leaf Hopper (3.5 " net pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: Here is another selfing of a classic that has been out of commerce for a while, but one of the all-time great winter blooming cluster flower hybrids.   Photos show the parent used and its potential to produce an eye popping specimen with long lasting flowers.   This orchid made its debut in 1974.
cards.name: Cattlianthe Gold Digger ('Fuchs Mandarin' x self) 3.5" pot seedling

cards.desc: This is a division off of a plant in the photos from Marble Branch Farms obtained from Murray De La Fuentes years ago and has good dark color and neat habits.   Blooms in early winter and eventually becomes a showy specimen.
cards.name: Laelia rubescens 6" net pot with hanger in spike

attachments.name: Laelia rubescens Murray De la Fuentes.jpg
laelia rubescens lav type best nov 04.jpg

cards.desc: Donated by Veronique Perrot - a nice typical form of this easily grown orchid, from Central America.   Considered one of the hardiest species to grow.
cards.name: Guarianthe bowringiana blooming size

cards.desc: A division off a plant Marble Branch Farms has had for many years, from the original batch of this Bc. Richard Mueller x Mcp. tibicinis hybrid made by Roy Tokunaga in 1998.   The mother plant is almost constantly in bloom. Flowers open red/orange and mature to yellow with spotted lip.  An outstanding plant - tested virus free.
cards.name: Myrmecatavola Tiger Lily - 6" net pot division

cards.desc: A cross between C. (Sophronitis) brevipenduculata and C. (Laelia) sincorana, both dwarf species from the interior of Brazil.   Give this one very good drainage, very bright light and regular watering with quick drying in between.   Can form a specimen plant in a 4 inch pot! Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Cattleya Roya Evelyn 'Floraform' AM/AOS - blooming size division

cards.desc: A real mix of species in the background of this orchid should keep it compact and easy to flower.    The photo is an example and may not be exactly the same as this specific plant. Donated by Cathy Meincer
cards.name: Cattlianthe Love Excellence

cards.desc: A clumping species with grassy leaves from Mexico and Central America that can produce numerous sprays of flowers in late spring into summer.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Encyclia bractescens

cards.desc:
A smaller growing species from coastal Brazil with wiry stems of fairly large two toned orchid pink flowers in mid to late summer.   Water this species year round with only a bit less water in winter
.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Encyclia dichroma

cards.desc: The albino form of a compact species widespread in lower and higher elevations of Mexico and Central America.   Wiry stems make clusters of blooms in late fall into winter.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Laelia rubescens forma alba

cards.desc: A desirable and hard to find cross done by Stewart's Orchids in 1979.   Very compact with comparatively large white flowers with a dark throat and a touch of yellow in the lip.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Laeliocattleya Dubescens (Cattleya Dubiosa (1890) x Laelia rubescens) 'Maui Beauty' AM/AOS

cards.desc: One of the earlier C. Beaufort hybrids that is compact and reliable with medium sized sunny yellow blooms, sometimes tinged with red.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Rhyncattleanthe Free Spirit 'Miami Sun'

cards.desc: A very nice cross betweern C. Beaufort and Rlc. Toshie Aoki.   This version has compact growth with lovely yellow flowers with a red lip and sometimes small red flares.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Rhyncolaeliocattleya Little Toshie 'Yellow Rose' HCC/AOS

cards.desc: Photo is representative of this cross that came out in 1962.     Compact grower with yellow, to yellow-orange clusters, most likely in winter.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Cattlianthe [Ctt.]  El Cerrito  (Gur. aurantiaca x C. crispata)

cards.desc: A real stunner with very lager deep lavender blooms with rich yellow throats and lots of fragrance.  Descended from C. Irene Finney and Rlc. Oconee.   This plant has two leads in sheath with buds developing.
cards.name: Rhyncolaeliocattleya akatsuka Fiftieth Anniversary 'Volcano Queen' - Mature plant with 2 sheaths in bud

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.   One of the Brazilian species moved to Cattleya in 2009.   From the mountains of SE Brazil just a bit inland from the coast.   Fall blooming.   Plants are fairly compact and produce distinct, upward facing flower.
cards.name: Cattleya (syn. Laelia) perrinii (small seedling)
Brassoepidendrum Green Dragon (Epi. magnoliae  B. nodosa)
Epi. magnoliae x Rth. Cherry Suisse

cards.desc: An exciting new introduction from Australia that stays compact and produces upright spikes of very unusual spotted flowers primarily in winter.  It is 50%  Cym. canaliculatum which is warm growing and 25% Cym. floribundum which keeps the plant size down.  Received and Award of Distinction from the Orchid Society Council of Victoria, Australia.
cards.name: Cymbidium Spark Sprite 'Sparky' (5.5" pot beginning to spike)

cards.desc: This Cymbidium is like a scaled down standard with strong upright spikes of lovely pastel and red flowers.   It has Cym. ensifolium for warmth tolerance and Cym. floribundum for smaller scale growth.   Can bloom twice per year.
cards.name: Cymbidium Street of Gold 'Mana' - warmth tolerent - 4" pot in bud

attachments.name: cym street of gold whole spike.webp

cards.desc: This unusual cross between Cym. devonianum and Cym. erythrostylum is quite compact and produces semi pendant spikes of dusty rose flowers with a dark lip in winter.  Mature plants can have many spikes at once.
cards.name: Cymbidium Devon Odyssey (4" pot blooming size)

cards.desc: This Marble Branch Farms cross (photo shows exact parents) will produce showers of pendant blooms in winter once mature, and should grow fast.  Both parents of Little Black Sambo were used with Cym. devonianum in the 1960's to create popular and successful hybrids, Cym. Cricket 1964 (devonianum x madidum) and Cym. Pied Piper 1968 (devonianum x canaliculatum).   But you would search high and low to find a division of those available today.   There are award records of these hybrids with hundreds of blooms open at once.   Expect medium sized, robust plants with wider than typical foliage producing pendant spikes with 30 or more flowers each.   Not yet available for sale by Marble Branch Farms.
cards.name: Cymbidium Little Black Sambo x devonianum (3.5" pot seedling)

attachments.name: 2911 cym little black sambo x devonianum.jpg

cards.desc: A really cool species from Southeast China that stays small and has flowers with lots of "personality."
cards.name: Paphiopedilum henryanum (2.5" pot with 2 spikes)

cards.desc:
A small sized, warm to cold growing lithophyte found only in Northern Vietnam in primary, broad leaf, evergreen forests on highly eroded, limestone cliffs and mountains in narrow crevasses at elevations of 40 to 750 meters. -- Source: Jay Pfahl's IOSPE at www.orchidspecies.com
A very cool, uncommon, hard to find species!
cards.name: Paphiopedilum tranlienanum (2.5" pot spiking)

cards.desc:
From the Paph. Paradise website:  "Paphiopedilum christensonianum was originally considered to be a variety of Paphiopedilum gratrixianum. In the recent checklist of Paphiopedilum species, Harold Koopowitz separated them and gave Paph christensonianum status as its own species. Whatever the status, our observations have been that this species is a more compact grower. It forms large clumps very quickly and makes an impressive specimen.

The flowers of this species are wonderfully colored. They have combinations of yellow, orange, with pink and dark purple. They also have a nice glossy texture.

This species grows quickly and flowers easily, with no special requirements. It can be grown along side mottled leaf species and hybrids, or even complex hybrids."
cards.name: Paphiopedilum gratrixianum variety christensonianum (3.5" budding plant)

cards.desc:
From the Paph. Paradise website:  "Paphiopedilum barbatum var. nigritum is a very compact growing species. It could be categorized as a miniature. The plants have attractive mottled foliage and can form specimen plants in a 3.5 pot. Some people view this as a separate species, perhaps it will be separated some day.

This is an easy plant to grow and bloom. They are not demanding and will reward you with flowers in the spring and summer months."
cards.name: Paphiopedilum barbatum var. nigritum (2.5" pot in bloom)

cards.desc: A nice species that stays very compact and is clumping and free blooming from late summer to early winter.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum charlesworthii (3.5" pot in bloom with second bud coming)

cards.desc: A showy, easily grown "Maudiae Type" with wide spreading flowers that have boldly spotted petals and lots of character.   This plant is producing a second flower from the same bloom spike.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum Luna Spots - in bloom with second bud

cards.desc: A nice, easy to grow "Maudiae Type" from Graham Wood of Lehua Orchids.   This example has great contrast in the flower colors and mottling of the foliage.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum Mistically Macabre - in bloom

cards.desc: A first blooming example of a great vinicolor hybrid just registered in 2018 from Lehua Orchids.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum Memoria Vickie Lynn Nagy - in flower - photo coming

cards.desc: Another recent introduction from Lehua Orchids with lots of great petal spotting contrasting with the bright white background of the dorsal sepal.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum Macabre Flutter - in flower - photo coming

cards.desc: Large pink flowers with undulating petals.
cards.name: Phragmipedium Incan Treasure (kovachii x longifolium) (in bud)

cards.desc: Fast growing bloomer that is "semi sequential" with up to 7 or more flowers on the stem, several open at a time, and sometimes the spike continues to grow and produce a few more.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum Mamie WIlson (lowii album x primulinum album) - in spike

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.   	
Paph. Hsinying Luke 'Omaha' AM/AOS x adductum var. anitum 'Ace' AM/AOS
anitum has been proved to be a great parent and specially with Brachy. Omaha is very round and large. First few bloomed have burgundy color flowers with dark chocolate stripes.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum (Hsyinying Luke x adductum var. anitum)

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. stonei x sib ('New Dimension' x 'The Best')
New Dimension is one of the best from our PAS0030. The Best is originated from late Ray Rands collection and it is the best stonei he had. Now we crossed New Dimension back to one of it's parent.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum stonei

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. supardii x sib ('Dragon Dance' x 'Golden Boy')
Both parents are from second germination line breeding of this species. Both parents have five flowers.
cards.name: Paphiopedilum supardii

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. rothschildianum x sib ('Giant Wings' GM/WOC x 'X-Hot' SSM/JOGA)
Sibling cross of two of the best Japanese breeding! Giant Wings awarded for his dark color at the WOC while X-Hot is GM quality and is very dark color. This is our best sibling cross of Japanese Strain!
cards.name: Paphiopedilum rothschildianum

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. rothschildianum x sib ('Giant Wings' GM/WOC x '2nd Dimension')
We all know about Giant Wings - from one of the best Japanese breeding. 2nd Dimension first bloomed with four gigantic flowers with almost 7cm dorsal and 30cm ns. We look for color, size and form!
cards.name: Paphiopedilum rothschidianum

cards.desc:
From Orchid Inn.
Paph. haynaldianum (Purple Wings x Ron)
cards.name: Paphiopedilum haynaldianum

cards.desc: A very showy hybrid of two "antelope" species with very long lasting spikes that will come off mature growths in different locations for years.  Requires a bit of space, but smaller than Den. stratiotes.
cards.name: Dendrobium Samarai (attenatum x stratiotes) (5.5" pot spiking)

cards.desc: A species that is rarely seen but rewarding to grow.   From a range of elevations in Papua New Guinea, it will bloom on both leafy and leafless older canes sporadically throughout the year with long lasting candy pink flowers with paler edges and an orange lip.   Water regularly with good drainage year round.
cards.name: Dendrobium pseudoglomeratum (4" basket blooming size)

cards.desc: One of the "must have" species that hasn't been in commerce for long.  Named after Lake Toba in northern Sumatra where it grows in mountain forests with year round rainfall and mild temperatures.  Flowers can be up to 4" across from tip to tip.
cards.name: Dendrobium tobaense var. giganteum (3.5" pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: Known in Indonesia as the "Tooth Brush Orchid" because the flowers all face in one direction.   They are borne on the upper portions of bare canes in winter, when the plants receive a drier rest period.   Blooming size plants of this species are hard to find and expensive.
cards.name: Dendrobium secundum (3.5" pot seedling)

cards.desc: A new hybrid that is 3/4 Den. tangerinum and 1/4 Den. attenatum, creating and medium sized plant with wonderful arching spikes of very long lasting "antelope" style flowers off an on at almost any time of the year.  Mature growths flower multiple times over several years.
cards.name: Dendrobium Luwin Park x tangerinum (3.5" pot spiking plant)

cards.desc: This compact growing "semi-antelope" Dendrobium is named after the wife of AOS Judge Harry Gallis of Durham, NC.   It can make a profusion of long lasting purple flowers of evergreen canes that reflower for years.
cards.name: Dendrobium Susie Gallis (Hawaiian Ministripe x Blue Twinkle) 3.5" pot in bloom

cards.desc: An easily grown Australian species that stays small but can make a wonderful specimen in time.   This form has pink and white variegation on the leaves, that matures to white, and similar to the photo.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Dendrobium kingianum (tricolor variegated leaf florm)

cards.desc: A semi-antelope hybrid from 1979 that is kept compact by being 50% Den. canaliculatum, a dwarf species from northern Australia.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Dendrobium Banana Royal

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.  Dendrobium dearei is considered the warmest growing species with evergreen canes and white flowers from the Philippines.   Despite the papery texture, the flowers last two months or longer.   It does not want a winter rest and grows best above 60F.
cards.name: Dendrobium dearei (two seedlings)

cards.desc: Donated by ABG.   This species lives up to its name with spectacular curly flowers, most heavily in winter.   Flowers are long lasting.   Plants are quick growing but do become large over time.
cards.name: Dendrobium spectabile (multiple small seedlings)

cards.desc: A miniature, creeping species from the coastal mountains of Venezuela with small, but brilliantly colored flowers, primarily in late fall into winter, but occasionally at any other time of the year as well.
cards.name: Maxillaria sophronitis (4" basket blooming size)

cards.desc: One of the very reliable and free flowering Brassia hybrids.  Strong upright spikes of up to a dozen spidery flowers.
cards.name: Brascidostele Gilded Tower 'Yellow Star' - In flower

cards.desc:
A good mix of compact Gomesa species and tough as nails Oncidium species makes upright spikes of flowers with huge yellow lips almost 3" across and beautifully tigered sepals and petals
.
cards.name: Oncidesa Jiuhbao Gold 'Tainan' AM/AOS - in flower

cards.desc: An easy growing and floriferous child of Ons. Catatante is easy and fast growing, with branched spikes of showy deep orange and yellow flowers at any time of the year on recently matured growths.
cards.name: Oncostele Firecat 'King Snake' - In bloom

cards.desc: http://www.orchidspecies.com/cischsheehaniae.htm
cards.name: Cischweinfia sheehanae (blooming size)

cards.desc: A lovely dwarf species from the coastal mountains of Brazil.   Donated by Cathy Meincer
cards.name: Gomesa croesus

cards.desc: A cross of two small growing species from Brazil, Oncidium harrisonianum and Grandiphyllum edwalii.   The genus Grandiphyllum was split off from Oncidium in 2006 and includes about 8 species, all from Brazil.  Despite the name, they are all small growing plants.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Grandicidium [Gdi.] Monica's Lovely

cards.desc: A Tulmnia type that based on similar crosses should have flowers in the yellow/orange shades with speckling.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Rodrumnia [Rrm.] Just Splendid (no photo available)

cards.desc: The 'Lemon Drop' form produces yellow flowers with no darker markings of good size on rather compact plants.   Fully mature plants can have up to 50 or more flowers in a large, branched spike.
cards.name: Oncidesa Sweet Sugar 'Lemon Drop' - in bloom

cards.desc: Compact growing type derived from Phal. pulcherrima.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Phalaenopsis Fire Cracker

cards.desc: KS Happy Eagle X tetraspis #C1.  Photo is an example, color can vary a bit.
cards.name: Phalaenopsis Yaphon Oh Mygod (blooming size)

cards.desc: Very fragrant species.

cards.desc: Once classed as a Vanda, this Southeast Asian species is very slender and terete with beautiful butterfly-like flowers in later summer into fall.   Temperature tolerant and may bloom better if exposed to nights int he 50's in winter.
cards.name: Holcoglossum wangii (2.5" basket in bloom)

cards.desc: A small species from southern Japan, the Ryukyu Islands and Taiwan that produces clusters of small, but colorful flowers in late summer.    Very temperature tolerant, but wants plenty of water in summer and somewhat less in winter.
cards.name: Gastrochilus japonicus 2.5" pot/basket near blooming size

cards.desc: http://www.orchidspecies.com/grosumscosa.htm
cards.name: Grosourdya muscosa (near blooming size)

cards.desc: A well known and beloved species from Japan, Korea and nearby islands that is small and clump forming, with sprays of wonderfully fragrant (usually at night) flowers mainly in summer.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Vanda [V.] falcata (syn. Neofinetia falcata)

cards.desc: http://www.orchidspecies.com/cryptelatus.htm
cards.name: Cryptopus elatus (near blooming size)

cards.name: Oeoniella polystachys (blooming size)

cards.desc: A wonderful Asian terrestrial with bright flourescent orange flowers that are  very eye catching.   Plants go dormant in winter and should not be watered while they rest as tubers in the pot.  Can multiply into a showy clump in just a few years.
cards.name: Habenaria rhodocheila 2.5" pot in bloom

cards.desc: The flowers on this primary hybrid between Habenaria medusae and Pecteilis radiata can be almost three inches from tip to tip.   Plants require total rest from water in winter while they hibernate as tubers, then plentiful water and feeding while growing.   Very rare in cultivation still and small plants like this one sell for high prices when you can find them.
cards.name: Pectabenaria Wow's White Fairies (2.5" pot seedling)

cards.desc: An unusual species from Mindanao Island in the Philippines that produces inflorescences out of the center of developing new growths that will bloom one flower at a time for an extended period, sometimes as many as 20 blooms before the spike is done.  Fairly large flowers are pure white with a cinnamon colored lip.
cards.name: Coelogyne usitana (3.5" pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: This Chysis hybrid introduced by Carter and Holmes in 2011 has already garnered 8 Awards of Merit from the American Orchid Society, with scores going as high as 88 points.   It does not seem to be, however, currently commercially available, so here is your chance.   Chysis prefer to have a somewhat drier period in winter and can grow into spectacular plants.   Flowers come tucked in with developing new growth.
cards.name: Chysis Maritza Blielecki (2" pot near blooming size)

cards.desc: Donated by Nicholas Rust.   One of the few fragrant species of Habenaria, with small two toned pink flowers.    Needs a total rest after flowering until tubers begin to grow again in spring.
cards.name: Habenarie erichmichelii (blooming size tuber)

cards.desc: A hybrid between Hab. rhodocheila and Hab. roebelinii.    Needs a total rest after flowering until tubers begin to grow again in spring. Donated by Nicholas Rust.
cards.name: Habenaria Hampson (blooming size tuber)

cards.desc: This Habenaria mixes three species, Hab. carnea, Hab. rhodocheila and Hab. erichmichelii.  Needs a total rest after flowering until tubers begin to grow again in spring. Donated by Nicholas Rust.
cards.name: Habenaria Raingreen's Pink Paw (blooming size tuber

cards.desc: Donated by Nicholas Rust.  From the Orchidspecies.com website "Found in Swaziland, Natal and Transvaal South Africa under trees along streams, dry gullies or rock bluffs at elevations of 600 to 1200 meters as a small to medium sized, cool to cold growing terrrestrial with an erect stem carrying cauline, narrow, often withering at blooming leaves that blooms in the fall on a terminal, erect, laxly to rather densely 15 to 40 flowered inflorescence"
cards.name: Bonatea saundersioides - 1 Near Blooming Size tuber

cards.desc: Donated by Nicholas Rust.   Very difficult to fine yellow flowered species.
cards.name: Habenaria xanthocheila - 1 small Blooming Size tuber

cards.desc: Donated by Nicholas Rust, this cross combines Hab. medusa with Hab. rhodocheila and erichmichelii.    Habenaria go completely dormant in winter and survive as tubers.
cards.name: Habenaria Raingreen's Ice Bird - 1 tuber

cards.desc: Donated by Cathy Meincer.   Widespread in Asia and the Pacific Islands and naturalized as a roadside plant in hawaii.   Plants can be tall, with grassy leaves and topped by sequentially flowering inflorescences that can produce up to 20, cattleya-like flowers in succession.   Photo is an example, some plants produce darker or lighter flowers.
cards.name: Arundina [Ar.] graminifolia (syn. Arundina caespitosa)

cards.desc: Donated by Cathy Meincer, this cross, registered over 35 years ago, is Masd. veitchiana x infracta.   The latter species will lend warmth tolerance.
cards.name: Masdevallia Marguerite '#2' HCC/AOS

cards.desc: This orchid has gone by many names but was placed in Aerangis in 2012.    From the mountains of the Comoros Islands, sprays of tiny orange flowers in abundance from a compact plant.
cards.name: Aerangis hariotiana (syn. Microtenangis hariotiana)

cards.desc: A warm growing species from Central and South America with fan like growth and numerous tiny flowers in long sprays.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Ornithocephalis bicornis

cards.desc: A small pleurothalid from Mexico and Guatemala.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Stelis [Ste.] emarginata (sym. Pleurothallis tubata)

cards.desc: A warm growing pleurothallid type from Mexico, Central and South America.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Specklinia [Spe.] brighamii

cards.desc: A small growing pleurothallid from Costa Rica and Panama.  Donated by Cathy Meincer.
cards.name: Specklinia [Spe.] costaricensis

cards.desc: A variable species from the Caribbean, Central and South America.   Donated by Cathy Meincer.  Photo is representative, but colors vary.
cards.name: Pleurothallis [Pths.] picta (syn. Specklinia picta)

cards.name: Graphorkis concolor var. alphabetica (near blooming size)

cards.desc:
Jay Pfahl describes Oeceoclades decaryana as "Medium sized, hot to warm growing terrestrial with ovoid pseudobulbs carrying 2, linear to lanceolate, narrowing below into a petiolate base, leathery, gray-green with blue gray and white-gray blotched leaves and blooms in the summer through fall on a basal, unbranched, 8 to 16 inches [20 to 40 cm] long, loosely 10 to 20 flowered inflorescence." 
Oeceoclades maculata is found in Africa from Kenya in the north to Tanzania and Uganda, spreading westward throughout tropical Africa to Liberia and southward to Angola and Natal in South Africa. This species is widely distributed in South America and the Caribbean, and has recently been reported as spreading throughout Florida. I
cards.name: Oeceoclades (decaryana x monophylla[syn. maculata] ) (blooming size)

cards.desc: http://www.orchidspecies.com/chysisbractescens.htm
cards.name: Chysis bractescens (near blooming size)

cards.desc: "Large sized, hot growing epiphyte, lithophyte or terrestrial with roots that only arise from the base [a major difference with the related Epi radicans that has roots any where on the stem] and erect, non-swollen, cane-like stems enveloped by grayish sheaths and carrying 6 to 10, subcoriaceous, elliptic, bilobed basally clasping leaves that blooms in the winter through spring on a terminal, to 20 inches [to 50 cm] long, congested, successively flowered, racemose inflorescence with the several flowers held in an umbel at the apex. "
cards.name: Epidendrum baumannianum (seedling)
